This plot shows all variables plotted at once. The arrows show which direction each variable influences each point. However, the plot is confusing and only accounts for 37.55% of variability of the data.

Instead, we can separate variables into 4 distinct groupings:

Group 1 Group 2 Group 3 Group 4
cp age sex slope
num trestbps thal oldpeak
exang fbs
-thalach ca

G1: chest pain, heart disease severity, exercise induced angina, max heart rate

G2: age, blood pressure, high blood sugar, vessels colored by floursopy

G3: sex, defects

The 3 columns represent no heart defect, a fixed heart defect, and a reversible heart defect. This data shows that men are more likely to have a heart defect, as well as more likely for said heart defect to be fixed.

G4: slope of ST, ST depression from exercise

The conclusion we can draw from this group is that those who already have a down sloping ST at peak exercise are more likely to have said ST slope more negatively affected by exercise than those with a up sloping or flat ST. Also note that those with upsloping ST seem to have more outliers than the rest.
